"Petersen M.F., Steffensen J.F.","Preferred temperature of juvenile Atlantic cod Gadus morhua with different haemoglobin genotypes at normoxia and moderate hypoxia",2003,"Journal of Experimental Biology","206","2",,"359","364",,,10.1242/jeb.00111,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037255978&partnerID=40&md5=9fd2c44bd023a3040fbca2c2ee17f2dd","Marine Biological Laboratory, University of Copenhagen, Strandpromenaden 5, DK-3000 Helsingør, Denmark","Petersen, M.F., Marine Biological Laboratory, University of Copenhagen, Strandpromenaden 5, DK-3000 Helsingør, Denmark; Steffensen, J.F., Marine Biological Laboratory, University of Copenhagen, Strandpromenaden 5, DK-3000 Helsingør, Denmark","Atlantic cod Gadus morhua has polymorphic haemoglobin, which can be separated into two homozygous types, HbI-1 and HbI-2, and one heterozygous type HbI-1/2. The geographical distribution of Atlantic cod with the different haemoglobin types varies, with the HbI2 allele occurring at high frequency in northern regions, and the HbI1 allele dominant in warmer areas. To determine if temperature is a selective parameter in the distribution of the haemoglobin types, the preferred temperature of the homozygous genotypes HbI-1 and HbI-2 was measured. We found that HbI-2 cod preferred a temperature of 8.2±1.5°C while HbI-1 cod preferred 15.4±1.1°C, and this preference was significant. The effect of hypoxia (35% oxygen saturation) on the preferred temperature was also measured. Previous studies showed that the preferred temperature of fish decreases during hypoxia, and this was the case for HbI-1 cod, which preferred 9.8±1.8°C during hypoxia, whereas HbI-2 cod did not show this effect. The results indicate that environmental temperature changes will lead to a distributional change in the different haemoglobin types of Atlantic cod, global warming providing an advantage for HbI-1 cod. However, since HbI-1 cod prefer a low temperature under hypoxic conditions, a combination of increased water temperature and hypoxia could be unfavourable for Atlantic cod stocks.","Atlantic cod; Gadus morhua; Haemoglobin; Hypoxia; Preferred temperature; Swimming speed","hemoglobin; oxygen; sea water; acclimatization; allele; animal; anoxia; article; Atlantic Ocean; climate; fish; gene frequency; genetics; genotype; pathophysiology; physiology; temperature; Acclimatization; Alleles; Animals; Anoxia; Atlantic Ocean; Climate; Fishes; Gene Frequency; Genotype; Hemoglobins; Oxygen; Seawater; Temperature; Animalia; Gadus; Gadus morhua",,"hemoglobin, 9008-02-0; oxygen, 7782-44-7; Hemoglobins; Oxygen, 7782-44-7",,,,"Bejda, A.J., Studholme, A.L., Olla, B.L., Behavioral responses of red hake, Urophycis chuss, to decreasing concentrations of dissolved oxygen (1987) Env. Biol. Fish., 19, pp. 261-268; Brett, J.R., Energetic responses of salmon to temperature. A study of some thermal relations in the physiology and freshwater ecology of sockeye salmon (Oncorhynchus nerka) (1971) Am. Zool., 11, pp. 99-113; Brix, O., Forås, E., Strand, I., Genetic variation and functional properties of Atlantic cod hemoglobins: Introducing a modified tonometric method for studying fragile hemoglobins (1998) Comp. Biochem. Physiol., 119 A, pp. 575-583; Chabot, D., Dutil, J.-D., Reduced growth of Atlantic cod in nonlethal hypoxic conditions (1999) J. Fish Biol., 55, pp. 472-491; Clark, D.S., Green, J.M., Seasonal variation in temperature preference of juvenile Atlantic cod (Gadus morhua), with evidence supporting an energetic basis for their diel vertical migration (1991) Can. J. Zool., 69, pp. 1302-1307; Despatie, S.P., Castonguay, M., Chabot, D., Audet, C., Final thermal preferendum of Atlantic cod: Effect of food ration (2001) Trans. Amer. Fish. Soc., 130, pp. 263-275; Dizon, A.E., Effect of dissolved oxygen concentration and salinity on the swimming speed of two species of tunas (1977) Fishery Bull. Fish Wildlife Serv. US, 75, pp. 649-653; Frydenberg, O., Møller, D., Nævdal, G., Sick, K., Hae